It would be depending on the country. At least in Japan, any people wouldn't expect that `alphaNumeric()` returns true against our word characters such as hiragana (e.g. `にほんご`), katakana (e.g. `ニホンゴ`), and kanji (e.g. `日本語`). And they would use custom validation rules such as isHIragana, isKatakana, and isKanji. I don't think it should be the part of the core library though.

As another option, we could use the `[[:alnum:]]` pre-defined character class of PCRE instead. By default, the `u` modifier should not be used, and it can be used optionally. Though `/[[:alnum:]]/u` also returns `1` against `日本語`, I don't mind it as long as it is not a default behavior.

@ADmad or @saeideng might have another opinion though. I think they are using yet another word characters in their language. Also umlaut characters in German should be considered.
